# Rust testing

Pair with `../general/tdd.md` (the cycle and the four pillars) and
`../general/testing.md` (where each kind of test lives).

## Test placement

Rust's convention is **unit tests live inline next to the code they
test**, integration tests live in `tests/` at the crate root.

```
crate/
├── src/
│   ├── lib.rs
│   └── orders.rs        ← #[cfg(test)] mod tests { ... } at the bottom
├── tests/
│   ├── orders_e2e.rs    ← integration tests
│   └── common/
│       └── mod.rs       ← shared test helpers (note the `/mod.rs`)
└── benches/
    └── orders.rs        ← criterion benchmarks
```

Within this project's DDD layout:

- `tests/unit/` is a convention placeholder. Rust unit tests *belong
  inline*. The directory exists for symmetry with other languages and
  may stay empty (the post-generation hook will prefix it `_unit/`).
- `tests/integration/` corresponds to Rust's top-level `tests/`
  directory — cross-module tests against real or in-memory adapters.
- `tests/e2e/` — black-box tests through the public binary boundary.
- `tests/performance/` — `criterion` benchmarks.

## Running

| What | Command (recipe) | Underlying |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Everything | `just rust-test` | `cargo test --all-features --all-targets` |
| One test by name | — | `cargo test refund` |
| One test, exact | — | `cargo test refund_when_unpaid -- --exact` |
| With nocapture (println output) | — | `cargo test -- --nocapture` |
| In a single thread | — | `cargo test -- --test-threads=1` |
| One integration file | — | `cargo test --test orders_e2e` |
| Doc tests | — | `cargo test --doc` |
| Benches (with nightly or criterion) | — | `cargo bench` |

For faster runs, install `cargo-nextest` and use `cargo nextest run`
instead of `cargo test`.

## Anatomy of a test

```rust
#[test]
fn refund_when_paid_marks_as_refunded() {
    // Arrange
    let mut order = Order::placed(items(), money(100, "USD"));
    order.mark_paid();

    // Act
    order.refund("customer requested").unwrap();

    // Assert
    assert_eq!(order.status, OrderStatus::Refunded);
    assert!(order.refunded_at.is_some());
}
```

- AAA layout. Blank lines between phases.
- One state-changing call in Act.
- One logical outcome in Assert; multiple `assert!`s checking facets
  of it are fine.

Inside `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`, `use super::*;` is the convention to
pull the module under test into scope.

## Naming

`fn <unit>_<condition>_<expected>()`:

- `email_normalisation_lowercases_domain`
- `refund_when_unpaid_returns_invalid_state`
- `paginate_returns_empty_when_offset_past_end`

The `fn` is the documentation. If the name doesn't fit, the test is
testing too many things.

## Doc tests double as examples

```rust
/// Adds two numbers.
///
/// ```
/// # use mycrate::add;
/// assert_eq!(add(2, 2), 4);
/// ```
pub fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 { a + b }
```

Doc tests run with `cargo test --doc`. They're *the* way to make
documentation examples stay correct over time.

## Property-based testing with `proptest`

```rust
use proptest::prelude::*;

proptest! {
    #[test]
    fn money_addition_is_commutative(a in 0u64..1_000_000, b in 0u64..1_000_000) {
        let m1 = Money::usd_cents(a);
        let m2 = Money::usd_cents(b);
        prop_assert_eq!(m1 + m2, m2 + m1);
    }
}
```

Use on value objects, parsers, and pure functions in `domain/`. Install
via `cargo add --dev proptest`.

`quickcheck` is the alternative; `proptest` has nicer shrinking, prefer
it.

## Snapshot testing with `insta`

For complex output (rendered text, formatted structs, JSON), `insta`
diffs against an on-disk snapshot. `cargo insta review` to update
intentionally.

## Benchmarking with `criterion`

```rust
// benches/orders.rs
use criterion::{black_box, criterion_group, criterion_main, Criterion};

fn bench_summarise(c: &mut Criterion) {
    let orders = fixtures::sample_orders(1000);
    c.bench_function("summarise 1000 orders", |b| {
        b.iter(|| summarise(black_box(&orders)))
    });
}

criterion_group!(benches, bench_summarise);
criterion_main!(benches);
```

`cargo bench` runs them. Criterion produces statistical confidence
intervals and detects regressions.

## Mocking — classical school

Same rule as the rest of the codebase: **mock only out-of-process
dependencies**. In Rust, this usually means:

- For in-process collaborators: parameterise on a trait and pass a
  hand-written in-memory implementation in tests.
- For HTTP/DB/etc.: `wiremock`, `testcontainers` (real container),
  or `mockall` (if you must — but the trait-and-fake approach is
  almost always cleaner).

```rust
struct InMemoryOrderRepo { orders: RefCell<HashMap<OrderId, Order>> }

impl OrderRepository for InMemoryOrderRepo {
    fn get(&self, id: OrderId) -> Option<Order> {
        self.orders.borrow().get(&id).cloned()
    }
    fn save(&self, order: Order) { self.orders.borrow_mut().insert(order.id, order); }
}
```

## What to test

| Layer | Coverage style |
| --- | --- |
| `domain` | High. Every invariant, every edge case. Pure functions love unit tests. |
| `application` | Integration tests against in-memory adapters. |
| `infrastructure` | Integration tests against a real instance via `testcontainers`. |
| `presentation` | Small set of e2e tests through the public CLI/HTTP boundary. |

## What NOT to test

- Trivial getters with no logic.
- Third-party crate behaviour (test your usage of it, not the crate).
- Implementation details that would force the test to change every
  refactor (private functions, internal struct fields).

## TDD with cargo

The full TDD ritual (mirrors `../general/tdd.md`):

1. `cargo test refund_when_unpaid -- --exact` — red.
2. Write the simplest implementation that turns it green.
3. `cargo test` (whole suite) — green everywhere.
4. Refactor with the suite as the safety net.
5. Commit.

Use `cargo watch -x test` (install `cargo-watch` once) to rerun on
every save during the cycle.
